**Hint:** Use `and` operator to check whether the `point` lies within the intervals i.e. between the start point and the end point. An `and` operator returns `True` when both conditions are `True`, otherwise returns `False`. For example,\n","- 5 < 6 **and** 5 < 7 ➞ Returns `True` as both conditions are `True`.\n","- 5 < 6 **and** 6 < 6 ➞ Returns `False` as only one condition is `True`.\n"]},{"cell_type":"code","metadata":{"id":"yYlWfTFxUx8C","colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/"},"executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1697285824985,"user_tz":-240,"elapsed":7,"user":{"displayName":"Taanush abraham","userId":"16497560746847074205"}},"outputId":"8ce1578f-c87f-48f6-9e42-d2b660913ed3"},"source":["# Solution:\n","def count_overlapping(lst,p):\n","  c=0\n","  for i in lst:\n","    if p>=i[0] and p<=i[1]:\n","      c+=1\n","  return c\n","count_overlapping([[1, 2], [5, 8], [6, 9]], 7)"],"execution_count":2,"outputs":[{"output_type":"execute_result","data":{"text/plain":["2"]},"metadata":{},"execution_count":2}]},{"cell_type":"markdown","metadata":{"id":"PLSY4nu0UzCj"},"source":["In the above program we have passed the `intervals[]` list and the `point` (intersecting point) as parameters inside the `count_overlapping()` function.\n","\n","Inside this function, we have first created a `count` variable and initialized with `0` which will be used to store the number of intersecting intervals.\n","\n","Using a `for` loop we have iterated through the values i.e. the **starting point** and **end point** of each list.\n","\n","Inside this `for` loop we are checking two conditions using the `and` operator:\n","  \n","  1. The **starting point** is less than or equal to the `point` i.e. `x[0] <= point`.\n","\n","  2. The  `point` is less than or equal to **end point** i.e. `point <= x[1]`\n","\n","If both the above conditions are satisfied then it means that a given point lies with the particular `interval` and hence, we increment the value of `count` by 1.\n","\n","Finally, we have returned the value stored in `count` variable using the `return` statement."]},{"cell_type":"markdown","metadata":{"id":"ftOXrP5NUzsZ"},"source":["---"]},{"cell_type":"markdown","metadata":{"id":"BVT9G_baB1aq"},"source":["#### Activity 2: Armstrong Number\n","\n","Write a function which takes a number as input and returns `True` if the number is an Armstrong number else returns `False` using `while` loop.\n","\n","A number is an **Armstrong number** if the sum of cubes of each digit is equal to the number itself.\n","\n","**For example:**\n","\n","For the number 153: (1 x 1 x 1) + (5 x 5 x 5) + (3 x 3 x 3) = 153. Hence, 153 is an Armstrong number.\n","\n","**Hint:** For solving this problem, you need to separate each digit of the number using `%` operator and find the cube of each digit in a `while` loop. Also keep on adding the cube of digit obtained on each iteration and store it in a variable (let's say `sum`).\n","\n","Finally, you need to check whether the value stored in variable `sum` is equal to the original number using an `if` condition. Return `True` if the number in `sum` is same as that of the original number, else return `False`.\n"]},{"cell_type":"code","metadata":{"id":"0pIGxKG9B3mb","colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/"},"executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1697285965797,"user_tz":-240,"elapsed":332,"user":{"displayName":"Taanush abraham","userId":"16497560746847074205"}},"outputId":"feafb88d-4da2-4293-95d1-d264dcd3d30b"},"source":["# Function to check whether a number is Armstrong or not\n","def armstrong(n):\n","  s=str(n)\n","  r=0\n","  for i in s:\n","    r+=eval(i)**3\n","  if r==n:\n","    return True\n","  else:\n","    return False\n","armstrong()"],"execution_count":3,"outputs":[{"output_type":"execute_result","data":{"text/plain":["True"]},"metadata":{},"execution_count":3}]},{"cell_type":"markdown","metadata":{"id":"z2vDEItoB8yW"},"source":["In the above function we have created a temporary variable `temp` and assigned it with the value of original number.\n","\n","In the first iteration of the `while` loop (iterates till `temp` > 0 is True), we are separating last digit of the number in `temp` variable by using `temp % 10` and we are storing this digit in another variable `digit`.\n","\n","Next, we are calculating the cube i.e. `digit ** 3` and adding it with the value stored in sum which is initially `0`. We are storing the result in the `sum` variable.\n","\n","Next, we are dividing the value stored in `temp` by 10 using `temp // 10`. This will exclude the last digit of the original number that is stored in `temp` variable.\n","\n","This process is repeated until the value in `temp` reaches the 1st digit of the value stored in `temp`.\n","\n","Finally, we are checking whether the value stored in variable `sum` is equal to the value stored in variable `num` (original number) using an `if` condition."]},{"cell_type":"markdown","metadata":{"id":"IJIZASayCpEW"},"source":["---"]}]}